<fanfic id="434">
	<chapter title="Chapter 5: Use Your Illusion">
		<p>"Stop being a goof, Kaela," Joey ordered as Kaela decorated her face with smears of sparkling blue body glitter from her secret "outrageousness emergency" stash. "The boys will be here in fifteen minutes!"</p>
		<p>"Who's goofing?" Kaela asked innocently as she turned to Joey with incandescent eyelids and lips. "This is how I'm going." She grinned and waved a gob of the shiny gel at Joey, her eyebrow going up-- which Joey knew by now meant she was thinking something evil.</p>
		<p>"Oh no you don't. Stay away from me!" Joey jumped up from the bed but not in time to avoid Kaela's wrath, and she ended up with some sort of tribal-disco marks on her cheeks and nose. "Now you're really going to die!" Joey laughed as she pinned Kaela down and tickled her neck until she begged for mercy. Out of breath from laughing, they both collapsed on Joey's bed to compose themselves.</p>
		<p>"Well that was a real time saver," Kaela observed with an edge of sarcasm.</p>
		<p>"Hey, who started it?" Joey threw back, giggling.</p>
		<p>"Why, not little old me," Kaela insisted, putting on a southern belle accent as she pouted her lips.</p>
		<p>"Okay, truly, we have to stop. I need to wash my face now, you're on your own miss body glitter." Joey got up and headed towards the bathroom. She pulled her hair back and splashed water on her face quickly, hoping to be ready before the doorbell rang.</p>
		<p>Pacey checked himself out in the rearview mirror one more time as the truck pulled up in front of Joey's house. "What do you think, Dawson?" he asked nervously.</p>
		<p>"I think you'd better stop eyeballing yourself every thirty seconds in that thing, or we won't live to see Providence. You look stylish and debonair, okay?" The two grinned at each other as they got out and headed towards the front door.</p>
		<p>"It's just that this feels so...official, and everything. This is a *real* date, Dawson, and I want to carry it off like a real gentleman."</p>
		<p>Pacey's voice didn't have a note of its usual sarcasm, and Dawson was impressed that he was taking this all so seriously. Lucky for him, he was past the constant nervousness stage with Joey-- not that he didn't have a certain fluttering sensation somewhere in his own stomach...</p>
		<p>"Don't worry, Pace, ten bucks says she'll jump you before the night's over."</p>
		<p>"Have you no dignity, Dawson?" Pacey frowned at him with an air of mock indignance. "Just because you haven't had any in, what, twenty-four long hours? Poor baby..." Dawson was about to give a slightly rude reply when the door opened, with Bessie smiling at them on the other side.</p>
		<p>"Hi boys, come on in, I think they need a few more minutes." Bessie led Dawson and Pacey into the house, thinking how quickly the little boys who'd chased Joey down the hall with frogs from the back yard had grown into these handsome young men. She sighed quietly to herself, hoping Alexander wouldn't grow up quite as fast.</p>
		<p>"So where are you guys going tonight, anyway?" Bessie asked as she offered them each a soda.</p>
		<p>"It's a surprise," Dawson explained, "so you'll have to ask Joey when she gets home." He grinned as he thought of how Joey had pouted when he wouldn't tell her their destination, and how well she'd tried to "coax it out of him." But, to his credit, he hadn't budged, and then she'd been too riled up to break it off, so he got his reward anyway. He tried not to blush in front of Bessie.</p>
		<p>"We're almost ready!" Joey called down the hall, followed by a muffled burst of giggling. Dawson was glad Joey had gotten so close with Kaela; it was good for her to have some girl friends, and besides, she did need someone other than Dawson who she could really talk to, and Pacey didn't quite fit the bill.</p>
		<p>The three of them continued to make small talk for a few minutes more, until Joey and Kaela emerged from the depths. Dawson had instructed them that it was casual attire, but these days that still left a lot of leeway for...variations. Dawson thought momentarily that he ought to ask Pacey to drop him and Joey off at the nearest motel, and pick them up on the way back. Joey looked like a goddess. Her hair was pulled up into a twist, with one little strand falling over her cheek by her ear, and she was wearing a tight skirt, very un-Joey like, but a welcome change of pace. Her blue sweater was a bit on the short side, and exposed just enough skin to get Dawson's imagination going. He swallowed the lump in his throat as he stood up.</p>
		<p>Pacey, meanwhile, was having similar thoughts of his own. He still wasn't sure how Kaela felt about him; she was always nice to him when the four of them were together, but maybe she just didn't want to be rude to Joey's friends? Maybe she only laughed at all his jokes because she thought he was a real idiot. Maybe he should stop staring...but he'd never seen anything like her before. She was a real non-conformist, not a poser like most of Capeside. He thought that she'd probably never been to the Gap in her life, and it didn't bother him one bit. She was wearing a pair of jeans that were torn in some wonderful places, obviously not on purpose, but through constant wearing, and a long-sleeved waffle shirt that had a sort of low neck, which led him to notice the red glass bead around her neck on a pink ribbon. It really focused his attention, which was strange since he usually couldn't tear his gaze away from her eyes. They were so clear, they seemed to see more than normal eyes. But this bead had the opposite effect-- it made him feel like he could see a little into her.</p>
		<p>"Wow," Dawson and Pacey both said at once, under their breath. Joey kissed Dawson lightly on the cheek, while Kaela held back a bit.</p>
		<p>"Hey Pacey," she said, enthusiastically enough. "Sorry we kept you waiting."</p>
		<p>"We'd have waited a lot longer, believe me," Pacey said, taking a risk by kissing the back of her hand. She grinned shyly before pulling her hand away to get her coat.</p>
		<p>"Remember," Bessie said as the four of them made their way outside, "home by midnight."</p>
		<p>"Two," Joey said boldly.</p>
		<p>"One."</p>
		<p>"Deal." Joey smirked as she kissed Bessie goodbye, wondering why they always had to haggle, but feeling like she was getting quite good at it.</p>
		<p>When they got to the truck, they discovered it was a tight squeeze for four across the front seat, so Dawson suggested that Joey sit on his lap.</p>
		<p>"Are you sure about that?" Pacey asked. "It's going to be a long drive," he reminded him.</p>
		<p>"How long?" Kaela implored. "Can't you tell us where we're going now?"</p>
		<p>Dawson and Pacey looked at each other questioningly.</p>
		<p>"They'll probably figure it out once we get onto the highway anyway," Pacey pointed out, and Dawson agreed.</p>
		<p>"We are going," Dawson said dramatically, "to the Fire and Water festival."</p>
		<p>"In Providence?" Joey gasped. "That's over an hour away, Dawson!"</p>
		<p>"That's the beauty of modern technology, Jo," Dawson smiled at the truck as he kissed her behind her ear, which never failed to draw her attention.</p>
		<p>"I've heard it's really cool," Kaela said excitedly as they piled in, Joey ending up on Dawson's lap after all, and Kaela in the middle between them and Pacey. "They just had Waterplace park redone last year, it's supposed to be great." She pinched Pacey's arm playfully. "Was this your idea, brainiac?"</p>
		<p>"Ow," Pacey lamented with mock pain. "And this is how you thank me?" They laughed as Pacey started the car.</p>
		<hr/>
		<p>By the time they got off 95, they were all pretty hungry, and agreed to stop somewhere for dinner. Since the festival went all night, there was no rush. None of them really knew their way around, so they just drove up the street that the highway led onto. There seemed to be a lot of restaurants right there, so they parked and got out to explore.</p>
		<p>"How about the Z-Bar?" Pacey suggested, pointing across the street. "That looks cool and trendy, huh?"</p>
		<p>"Oooh, there's a Japanese place up there," Kaela said excitedly, looking up the hill.</p>
		<p>"How do you know it's Japanese?" Pacey asked skeptically.</p>
		<p>"Um, because it's called Tokyo?" Kaela grinned with an edge of sarcasm. She had definitely been spending too much time with Joey, Pacey thought. But he wanted her to have a good time, and he was man enough for some raw fish, wasn't he?</p>
		<p>"Okay, sure, does that sound good to you guys?" he offered to Dawson and Joey. Dawson agreed, but Joey was somewhat reticent.</p>
		<p>"I don't know, I'm not so good with exotic stuff...and I doubt they serve tartar sauce in that place."</p>
		<p>"Come on, Jojo, expand your horizons!" Kaela implored. "It's my favorite, you'll love it. I promise." Kaela was pulling Joey up the hill with one hand, already anticipating success. Joey relented, much to Dawson's surprise. She'd never even had Chinese until 8th grade, he remembered, and she hadn't been too enthusiastic about that either.</p>
		<p>"I can't believe you let her call you Jojo," Dawson said as they made their way toward the restaurant. "I tried that once and you punched me in the stomach."</p>
		<p>"Dawson, that was the fifth grade," Joey said, rolling her eyes. "And you were teasing me."</p>
		<p>"I was not," Dawson huffed with mock indignance.</p>
		<p>"Well I apologize for punching you five years ago, okay?" She stopped and put her arms around Dawson's neck. "Do you forgive me?"</p>
		<p>"Gee, I don't know," Dawson mused. Joey leaned into him and planted a kiss on him lips, gliding her tongue over his teeth. Then she pulled back and looked at him expectantly. "One more of those and you're off the hook."</p>
		<p>Dawson laughed as Joey pushed him away with a sly smile, keeping the upper hand as usual.</p>
		<p>"Don't push your luck."</p>
		<p>The restaurant was crowded, but they were seated quickly. They had to take off their shoes before they entered the dining room, where the tables were low and the seats were cushions. When they sat down, the hostess brought them a basket full of hot towels to wash their hands.</p>
		<p>"This is pretty cool," Pacey said as he surveyed his surroundings. "Not your average fish 'n chips place, but it has a certain charm..."</p>
		<p>Kaela gave his shoulder a playful whack, reprimanding his cockiness. "Give it a chance, will you?"</p>
		<p>"I said I would, didn't I?" They looked over their menus carefully, all of them electing cooked dishes except Kaela.</p>
		<p>"You're really going to eat raw fish?" Joey asked incredulously.</p>
		<p>"Sure, it's fabulous. And don't say eww, Jo, you've never tried it so you have no conception of what it might be like." Kaela took on a sudden pedantic tone as she lectured her friend on her palate.</p>
		<p>"Yes Ma'am," Joey said seriously, and laughed as Kaela stuck out her tongue.</p>
		<p>"Since this has become a night of adventure," Pacey said mysteriously, "how about topping it off with some Japanese beer?"</p>
		<p>They all looked at him blankly, and he put on a stern, mature face as he whipped out an ID card. "Hi, I'm Doug Whitter, nice to meet you."</p>
		<p>"Pacey!" Joey gasped as the rest of them giggled. "He's going to kill you. Literally! Of all the people whose ID you could steal, you pick the deputy? He'd bust your ass without giving it a second thought."</p>
		<p>Pacey shook his head at Joey's worried expression.</p>
		<p>"It's not like that, Jo. Look, he's never gonna know I have it, because it's outdated-- see? It expired last year, he has a new one, and this picture of him was taken right before he left for college. It's a dead ringer, eh?" Pacey held it up next to his own face and smiled as if he were in a commercial for something. They all had to agree, the resemblance was remarkable.</p>
		<p>"Well," Kaela said, beginning to look at bit sly herself, "if we're going to buy alcohol, don't bother with beer-- we should get Saki."</p>
		<p>"What's that?" Joey asked cautiously, not sure if she could handle another new experience in one night.</p>
		<p>"It's warm rice wine, and it's the traditional drink of friends to salute each other. You know, like it's good luck to drink it in good company."</p>
		<p>"Sounds good to me," Dawson said, still incredulous that Pacey had the balls to do this.</p>
		<p>"Okay," Joey agreed. The waitress came to their table a minute later and they ordered, Pacey looking so calm and debonair that she didn't even ask to see his ID, after all that. When the food came, they all found themselves eyeing Kaela's plate suspiciously.</p>
		<p>"What's that?" Joey asked, pointing to something red.</p>
		<p>"Tuna."</p>
		<p>"And what's that?" She pointed to something white on top of a ball of rice.</p>
		<p>"Squid."</p>
		<p>"Ewww!" Joey shrieked involuntarily, a little disappointed that she hadn't been able to act cooler about it. But raw squid was just more than she could handle.</p>
		<p>"All right, thanks for the editorial, Joey, let's just try the Saki, okay?" Kaela laughed it off even though she was a little irritated that Joey was being so closed minded.</p>
		<p>The Saki was quite a sight, though; it came in a ceramic jug, like a little pot of tea, and they all had tiny mugs which Pacey gallantly poured the steaming wine into.</p>
		<p>"This stuff is strong," Kaela warned them all, "so don't overdo it."</p>
		<p>They clicked their cups together in a toast, and sipped the wine carefully. Joey was surprised to find that she liked it, since she hadn't yet tasted any alcohol she liked-- not that she'd had all that much. But this was...well, she couldn't quite describe it, but it felt nice going down her throat, and it made her stomach feel warm. It made other parts of her feel warm, too, and she bit her lip as she wondered how long it would be until she got Dawson alone.</p>
		<p>They finished their meal in relative peace, the Saki taking the spotlight off Kaela's sushi. When the bill came, Pacey and Dawson tried to pay it, but Kaela and Joey refused.</p>
		<p>"What century do you think this is, Dawson?" Joey said emphatically as they all put in their money. "A man paying for a woman's dinner has some pretty serious sociological implications. It says you're making an investment, that you expect to get some return on it, you know?"</p>
		<p>"I just wanted to be a gentleman, Joey, you know I'd never--"</p>
		<p>"I didn't mean you personally, Dawson, I'm talking about a cultural infrastructure here that we're all part of."</p>
		<p>"Joey," Pacey said dryly, "why are you making me feel like I'm at school?"</p>
		<p>"Sorry if your brain can't handle the overload, I guess you're too caught up in your dissertation thesis to be able to process anything else."</p>
		<p>"Easy, guys," Kaela sighed as she put a hand one each other their shoulders. "If you can't play nice, you have to sit in time out."</p>
		<p>"Sorry 'Mom'," Joey giggled as she gave Kaela a kiss on the cheek.</p>
		<p>"It's hard not to act that way sometimes, with two little kids in the house," Kaela offered by way of apology.</p>
		<p>"You don't have to explain," Pacey said as he steered the group back out to the street. "We act like little kids all day, it's got to kick in eventually."</p>
		<p>By the time they left the restaurant, the sun had gone down, and they could see the torches lighting the way to Waterplace Park, where the festival was going on. Music floated through the evening air toward them, and they strolled happily in the direction of the activity. Dawson put his arm around Joey's shoulder, and she slipped her hand inside his jacket where her cold fingers met his warm back.</p>
		<p>"You are wicked," he whispered to her, and she kissed his ear in response. They began to fall behind a bit, and Kaela and Pacey walked on ahead of them.</p>
		<p>"...So how come you know so much about Japanese food?" Pacey asked, wondering if there was some underground Asian community in Capeside he didn't know about.</p>
		<p>"Oh, my cousin John-- he travels a lot, and he lived in Japan for a few years when I was younger. My mom and I went to visit him for Christmas when I was eight. I just got hooked."</p>
		<p>"Wow, that's cool," Pacey said shaking his head. "The furthest I've ever gotten from Capeside is Pittsburgh." He thought of all the experiences Kaela had had that he couldn't even imagine; he felt a little inadequate for a moment, but then he shook it off.</p>
		<p>"Hey, Pittsburgh's something!" Kaela laughed. "Anyway, you've got plenty of time."</p>
		<p>"Yeah, but the sooner the better. I've got to get away from Capeside, I can never be anything but the town loser there."</p>
		<p>"Don't say that," Kaela said softly, studying his face for a moment. "You're not going to spend the rest of your life in high school, you know. You can do anything you want, and people aren't going to think about what grade you got in sophomore Bio."</p>
		<p>She grinned and he sighed, wishing it were that simple.</p>
		<p>"You know something," he said, "you smile more than anyone else I know." She turned her glance down to her feet shyly, but her smile held its ground. "Really," Pacey persisted, "I don't know what you and Joey have in common."</p>
		<p>"Oh, everything," Kaela mused as she shook her head, her grin getting bigger. "Joey is-- oh, never mind."</p>
		<p>"No, I want to hear what you have to say," Pacey urged, and Kaela sighed, looking up at the starts for a moment.</p>
		<p>"Well, Joey is like someone I always knew, that I was just waiting to meet. Like we were together in a past life or something. I don't know, this is dumb, I just feel like...the day we met was like, 'where have you been all this time, I've been waiting for you'."</p>
		<p>She blushed, and Pacey wasn't quite sure what to say. Luckily, they found themselves standing directly in front of the festival entrance.</p>
		<p>"Hey, here we are," he observed, holding out his arm for her. "Shall we?"</p>
		<p>She nodded, and they made their towards the amphitheater, where there was a band and a beautiful display of burning wire sculptures floating down the river behind it.</p>
		<p>Joey and Dawson hadn't quite made it to the festival yet; they had been side-tracked by a lovely private spot behind the train station on the way. They were making out hungrily in the grass, and might have forgotten to even think of rejoining their friends if they hadn't had a police officer shine his flashlight in their faces.</p>
		<p>"This ain't a motel, you kids move along," he said sounding stern but bored. They were so surprised at being caught that they didn't even acknowledge his existence, but grabbed their jackets quickly and bolted around the building, laughing. When they got back to the street, they stopped to catch their breath, still laughing almost uncontrollably.</p>
		<p>"That was nuts, I feel like a criminal!" Dawson said as he straightened his shirt, which had gotten a bit tousled.</p>
		<p>"It feels kind of good, doesn't it?" Joey said mischievously, taking her time adjusting her own clothes, so as not to look suspicious.</p>
		<p>"You are a little devil, aren't you," Dawson remarked as he circled his arms around her waist for one more kiss before they began walking again.</p>
		<p>"What time is it, anyway?" Joey asked as she took Dawson's hand.</p>
		<p>"Almost eleven."</p>
		<p>"Shit, I hope we can find Kaela and Pacey. I told her she wouldn't have to be alone with him...hope he didn't try anything on her, I'd be forced to go to extreme measures."</p>
		<p>"Relax, Jo, Pacey wouldn't do anything disrespectful. For all his talk, he's a pretty nice guy underneath it all."</p>
		<p>"I'd agree with you, except I'd hate to go on record as saying Pacey's a nice guy..."</p>
		<p>Dawson shook his head and wondered what would happen if Joey and Pacey ever made peace. The sky might come crashing down, Armageddon, who knows?</p>
		<p>"Well we're here, anyway," Dawson noted as they approached the entrance. "Looks pretty cool. You ready?"</p>
		<p>Joey nodded, and they headed over to the lights on the river.</p>
		<p>Pacey and Kaela were indeed alone, but neither one was screaming for help. They sat on the far edge of the stone amphitheater, away from the crowd, trying out a few introductory kisses. Without putting too much thought into it, Pacey was pretty sure he liked what was going on, but after a minute Kaela pulled away.</p>
		<p>"What's wrong?" Pacey asked, licking his lips nervously, hoping he didn't taste gross.</p>
		<p>"Nothing," Kaela said sadly, which confused Pacey a bit. "Nothing is wrong...so why isn't anything right?"</p>
		<p>Pacey didn't respond, he just looked at her to communicate his intentions to listen. She met his eyes for a moment, and her own eyes welled up with tears.</p>
		<p>"You're a great guy, Pacey," she said quietly, her voice a little wobbly. "I mean, you're funny, and intelligent, and you listen..." her voice trailed off and Pacey's heart sank as he thought of all the times he should have gone to the gym.</p>
		<p>"What the hell is the matter with me?" She whispered.</p>
		<p>"Nothing's the matter with you, Kaela," Pacey said finally, betraying his confusion. "I don't understand-- I mean, I want to understand...you can trust me, you know."</p>
		<p>"You don't really, you don't want to know," she said shakily as she wiped her eyes on the back of her sleeve. "You'd probably hate me, and I wouldn't blame you."</p>
		<p>"Look, Kaela, I know we don't really know each other that well, but I like you-- I mean I don't just like you because you're beautiful, I like you as a person, you know, as a friend. The only thing you could say that would make me hate you would be that you hate me, so if you're not going to say that, then I can handle it."</p>
		<p>He smiled encouragingly at her, but this time she couldn't smile back. She just kept staring at her hands, nervously turning her thumb ring around her finger.</p>
		<p>"I thought..." she said quietly, almost whispering, "if I could just go along doing the things girls do, normal things, that it would just go away...shit, Pacey, I can't believe I'm telling you this."</p>
		<p>Pacey didn't say anything, as he began to realize what they were really talking about.</p>
		<p>"I've never said this out loud before."</p>
		<p>"You still haven't," he said gently. She looked up at him, and he saw that the tears in her eyes had spilled over down her cheeks, with new ones on the way.</p>
		<p>"I like hanging out with you, Pacey, and I like talking to you, and all of that...so why don't I like this?"</p>
		<p>"It's hard," Pacey said as he squeezed her hand, "to kiss someone when you're thinking of someone else."</p>
		<p>"What if that someone else is Joey?" She whispered, her eyes squeezed shut.</p>
		<p>"Then I'd tell you I've been there before, and there's not much hope."</p>
		<p>Kaela's mouth betrayed her in the beginning of a smile, even though the rest of her face was filled with misery and embarrassment.</p>
		<p>"It's not the same, Pacey, and you know it."</p>
		<p>"No, it's not," Pacey agreed, "but I'll tell you the same thing I tell my closet case brother every day-- it's not the end of the world to be gay."</p>
		<p>She looked up at him quickly, her eyes registering shock for a moment before she buried her face in her hands.</p>
		<p>"God, I hate that word," she mumbled through her tears. "it's almost as bad as..." She trailed off and he finished her sentence.</p>
		<p>"Lesbian?"</p>
		<p>He watched her eyebrows knit into a hateful expression that had seemed so foreign to her an hour ago.</p>
		<p>"All I can think of is women with shaved heads and leather jackets...ugh, I don't want to be that, Pacey."</p>
		<p>"You're not that, not at all, and I can't think of any reason why you should try to be."</p>
		<p>He took both her hands in his, forcing her to come out of hiding and look at him. "Who you love doesn't change who you are, you know...you're the same person you always were."</p>
		<p>"Yeah, I guess I was always fucked in the head."</p>
		<p>"Jesus, Kaela, don't say that! I know Capeside isn't exactly overflowing with gay culture or role models, but...but you've been all over the world, don't you know it's not seen as such a bad thing anymore?"</p>
		<p>"I don't know, Pacey, some places more than others, it's just...I don't know, she'd hate me if she knew, that's what counts."</p>
		<p>"No she wouldn't," Pacey said firmly. "Look, if I don't get through to you about anything else, I've got to get you to listen to this. Joey is the most caring person I know, not that I know too many other caring people. I've known her all my life, and she'd never turn on anyone she cares about. She knows what it feels like to be abandoned. I've seen you together," Pacey said as he took her chin in his hand, making her look at him. "And I know she cares about your friendship."</p>
		<p>She looked back down at the ground as soon as Pacey let go of her chin. He'd never imagined that this girl who seemed to be filled with sunshine and understanding could have such terrible self-esteem.</p>
		<p>"So you don't hate me?" she asked weakly, her eyes imploring.</p>
		<p>"Of course not, Kaela, I just never thought I'd be so jealous of Joey."</p>
		<p>He got a small grin out of her that time, but it was fleeting. "So when are you going to tell her?"</p>
		<p>"Never!" she said hotly, her cheeks flushed with shame. "Pacey, if you say one word, I swear--"</p>
		<p>"Relax, I won't say anything to anyone, I'd never betray your trust, Kaela."</p>
		<p>Pacey was shocked to see the fear in her eyes.</p>
		<p>"...Thanks," she sighed, catching her breath in her throat. "You really are a pretty great person, you know, Pacey," she said as she hugged him.</p>
		<p>He hugged her back, hoping if she couldn't believe his words, he could still show her that he was there for her.</p>
		<p>"Too bad neither of us can compete with Dawson."</p>
		<p>She pulled away and Pacey wiped a few tears off her cheek.</p>
		<p>"You know, it's never going to get any easier," Pacey said delicately, "unless you talk about it. With Jo, I mean. Crushes suck, it's like they eat you up inside if you don't let them out. Maybe you're not ready yet, but soon you will be. You'd be surprised..."</p>
		<p>She nodded, taking a deep breath and trying to pull herself together. Suddenly, they both looked up and noticed Joey and Dawson walking toward them.</p>
	</chapter>
	<chapter title="Chapter 6: Your Little Secret">
		<p>Joey broke into a run when she saw Kaela crying. She had always been at least half joking when she talked about hating Pacey, but now she was going to cut him dead. "You asshole," she hissed, "you're not going to live to see the sunrise." She put her arm protectively over Kaela's shoulder and pulled her away, before either she or Pacey had a chance to respond. Dawson just stood there dumbstruck, feeling as if he'd just been caught in the eye of a storm. He looked at Pacey incredulously.</p>
		<p>"Hey, man, don't give me that look! You know I didn't do anything to her, Jesus!" Pacey said with a look of disgust, thinking that his best friend actually thought he might try to force himself on a girl.</p>
		<p>"I wasn't thinking that, Pacey," Dawson shot back defensively. "It was just a weird situation. Ideally, no one cries on a first date."</p>
		<p>"Fuck you," Pacey muttered, getting up to leave.</p>
		<p>"Pacey, wait a second." Dawson grabbed his arm and sat him back down. "I'm sorry, that was really rude. Tell me what happened, I know you'd never do anything like that."</p>
		<p>Pacey sighed, trying tiredly to think of some sort of quasi-lie that might serve as cover for the girl he was hot for, who was hot for the last girl he'd been hot for...he couldn't think too clearly.</p>
		<p>"We were just talking, Dawson, and she got upset about something I'm not at liberty to disclose."</p>
		<p>"Oh really?" Dawson's eyebrows went up suspiciously, as he ran down a mental list of what those things might have been.</p>
		<p>"Yes, really. Look, if it were about me, I'd tell you in a second, but it's totally none of your business, or mine either, if you come right down to it, so I'd say we better just drop it."</p>
		<p>"Okay, okay, sheesh," Dawson sighed dissapointedly. "...but did you kiss her?" A grin was creeping over Dawson's face.</p>
		<p>"No."</p>
		<hr/>
		<p>"I'm sorry, Kaela, shit, I'm so sorry, I said I wouldn't leave you alone..." Joey's voice trailed off as she sat her friend down on the grass by the riverbed, stroking her hair as she hugged her. "I swear I'll kill him," she whispered as Kaela's tears quieted. She pulled back to look in her friend's eyes, assessing the damage. The fear she saw almost blew her mind.</p>
		<p>"Pacey didn't do anything, Jo," Kaela whispered as she tried to catch her breath. Joey was running her fingers though the hair at the back of Kaela's neck, softly, and Kaela wished for a moment that she could just sit there all night without having to say anything, or explain anything, and just stay safe and warm in Joey's quiet affection. But of course, silence wouldn't cut it for much longer.</p>
		<p>"What happened, Sweetheart?" Joey asked gently. Kaela looked at her for a moment, and then back down at the ground, her heart racing. She felt like a deer caught in headlights. A dozen fabrications flew to mind, perfectly good reasons she could be crying, but she knew she'd never be able to lie to Joey. She wanted to say it, she was dying to, she could even hear herself saying it.</p>
		<p>"I...God, Jo, I can't tell you." Her eyes filled with fresh tears as she spoke, watching Joey's face fall in an expression of deep hurt.</p>
		<p>"You can tell me anything, Kaela, you know that." Joey's own heart began to beat a little faster as the air around her seemed to get thicker. There was something tingling all around them, as if the whole world might shatter at the hugeness of what was coming. But what it was, Joey had absolutely no idea.</p>
		<p>"Anything but this, Joey," Kaela said shakily, hating herself as the words fell from her lips. "I'm sorry, I want to so much...but not now, I just can't."</p>
		<p>Joey nodded, and wrapped her arms around Kaela's bent frame fiercely, hugging her close until the tears melted into even breaths. Kaela put her head down on Joey's shoulder, letting herself be comforted as the sensation of being trampled set in on her. She took in a deep breath, breathing Joey in without really meaning to. Her hair smelled so good. She was so far away from safety, a million miles from where she wanted to be, but for a few silent moments, she could at least pretend the world was how she wanted it.</p>
		<p>"Wanna go get some coffee before we go home?" Joey asked quietly, disentangling herself slowly from the moment that hadn't quite been.</p>
		<p>"Yeah," Kaela sighed while she dried her eyes, sniffling as she made her way back to reality. They went back over to where they'd left the boys, who were looking a little less bewildered than they were.</p>
		<p>"Sorry, Pace," Joey said quickly, and Pacey nodded, but Joey wasn't even really looking. The awkwardness hung over them all faintly, like mist, until they entered the coffee shop. Once they had ordered, they realized they were back among a large group of teenagers, almost just like if they were hanging out at the Icehouse, and they all relaxed a little. They got their drinks to go, and once they were served, they headed back towards the truck. Pacey tried to keep Kaela's spirits light, telling dumb jokes and cracking on weird people they saw walking by. It seemed to work a little; she laughed a few times, at least, and the smile she usually wore wouldn't be held back much longer. It was a bit more reserved than her normal smile, but it was better than nothing.</p>
		<p>Joey, meanwhile, was desperate to understand what had just happened. A million possibilities ran through her head, but nothing that really made sense...and what on God's green earth could Kaela tell *Pacey* that she couldn't tell her? They barely even knew each other. Joey's instinct was to feel hurt, and a little rejected, but she couldn't keep feeling that way with Kaela holding onto her hand for dear life. She's not mad at you, Joey said to herself over and over. It's okay, she'll tell you when she's ready. As they all climbed into the truck, Joey leaned over and tucked a lock of hair behind Kaela's ear, kissing her forehead. Kaela didn't respond, but smiled a little. Joey sighed and put her head down on Dawson's shoulder, suddenly feeling very tired.</p>
		<p>"Joey, we're home." Dawson's voice in her ear was the first clue Joey had that she'd been asleep the entire trip back. Dazed, she looked up quickly, for a moment having no memory of the night's events, only a vague apprehension.</p>
		<p>"What time is it?" she asked foggily.</p>
		<p>"Quarter to one," Pacey said looking at his watch. "you're safe."</p>
		<p>She nodded, opening the door, and slid off Dawson's lap onto the less welcoming ground. Dawson got out next so that Kaela could get out, too, since she was sleeping at Joey's. For a moment, Pacey and Kaela were alone in the truck's cabin.</p>
		<p>"You gonna be okay tonight?" Pacey whispered to her, taking her hand protectively.</p>
		<p>"I don't know, Pacey, I'm scared," she admitted shakily.</p>
		<p>"Look, you can come stay at my house if you want, it'll give you some time to clear your head and get things together before you decide how you're going to handle this."</p>
		<p>"That's really nice of you to offer, but I can't bail on her now...you weren't there when we talked, it was...really, really intense, and if I leave now she's going to think I'm ditching her or something, I owe her more than that." Kaela bit her lip as she thought of how much harder it would be to keep her cool once she and Joey were alone.</p>
		<p>"Okay," Pacey sighed, "you know where I am if you need me." Kaela nodded and hugged him quickly, before slipping out of the safety of the truck, tentatively walking over to the front step where Joey stood waiting.</p>
		<p>Bessie, of course, was still awake when they walked in. "Hey," she said wearily, "so where'd you go?"</p>
		<p>"Providence," Joey said absently, hoping to keep the conversation to a minimum.</p>
		<p>"Neat, to the festival I bet. Was it fun?"</p>
		<p>"Mm-hmm. We're exhausted, though, so we'll see you in the morning, okay Bess?" Joey gave her sister a quick kiss on the cheek and, without waiting for a reply, took Kaela's hand and led her down the hall to her room. They changed silently into their pajamas, both with a million questions of the tip of their tongues but both afraid to speak first. Finally, when there was nothing left to do, Joey sat down on the bed and crossed her legs, bracing herself for-- what? "So are we going to talk?"</p>
		<p>Kaela felt her stomach do a few calisthenics, tugging on her hair before she could think of a reply. She crept to the edge of the bed and sat down cautiously, looking down at her hands.</p>
		<p>"I have no idea what I'm doing here, Jo...I just don't want to ruin everything."</p>
		<p>"Kaela, nothing you could say could ruin everything. You're my friend, I love you, whatever it is." Joey began to feel like she wasn't even in the room anymore, but watching from above, or on a TV screen. Yes, that's exactly what it was, another one of Dawson's convoluted screenplays, only this time Dawson wasn't calling the shots.</p>
		<p>Kaela felt the tears behind her eyes pressing to be let out, and she knew the next time she opened her mouth, there would be no stopping them. She breathed in a few very slow, deliberate breaths, and after a moment of cloudiness she regained control. On a whim, she reached over to Joey's desk and picked up the heavy volume of Spanish poetry the two of them had used in their presentation. Opening it, she flipped the pages tensely, having no idea what it was she was looking for until she got to it.</p>
		<i>
		<p>"Entre lo que veo y digo,</p>
		<p>entre lo que digo y callo,</p>
		<p>entre lo que callo y sueño,</p>
		<p>entre lo que sueño y olvido,</p>
		<p>la poesía."</p>
		</i>
		<p>She read it aloud quietly, not quite realizing she was using the poem to try to explain herself. Subtext seemed to be the only place where she was safe. Joey put her hand over Kaela's and closed the book, watching her tears fall on the heavy cloth cover.</p>
		<p>"Please, talk to me." Joey's eyes hunted for a sign, any sign, that she was getting somewhere. Kaela kept her eyes averted, her lip trembling as if she were holding in a scream.</p>
		<p>"I want to talk to you, Joey, I just...shit, why can't I do this? The only thing I want to do is say this to you." She finally met Joey's gaze; her crooked glance filled with love and concern almost broke Kaela's heart.</p>
		<p>"Okay," Joey said decisively, "this is what we're going to do. I'm getting up to go wash my face, and you sit here and take a minute to breathe. When I get back, you can tell me."</p>
		<p>Without waiting for confirmation, Joey quickly got up and left the room, leaving Kaela with no choice but to gather her strength. All she could think was that these were going to be the last five minutes of their friendship, Joey was about to hate her forever. She thought of all the innocent times Joey had hugged her from behind and played with her hair, having no idea the power she had, what she was doing to her. It has to stop now, Kaela told herself, beginning to feel terribly nauseous. She couldn't keep going like this, Pacey was right, it was consuming her. She couldn't write one more poem, couldn't spend one more night crying, she'd just splatter all over the room or throw herself against a brick wall.</p>
		<p>Joey spent longer than necessary scrubbing her face, feeling a heavy knot forming in her own stomach. Her usual ability to critically analyze any situation had vaporized into a vague, electric energy of certainty that something big was happening, something so big she was afraid to say it for fear that the very words would slice her throat to ribbons, wrap around her lungs until the whole world crashed down on her. Breathe, she told herself. Just breathe. Her face bright pink (from scrubbing, of course), Joey hesitantly pushed the bedroom door open, finding Kaela in the exact same position she'd left her in, knees pulled up as if she were being attacked, on the edge of the bed. Joey didn't say anything, just sat down next to her and put one hand gently on her cheek, looking unwaveringly into her clear blue eyes. Kaela pulled her eyes up to meet Joey's, still trembling. She saw herself at the edge of a cliff, looking over, toes right at the edge. One tiny shift in her weight would send her down, no going back. No more thinking, she just had to let herself fall. Without giving herself a moment to reconsider, she leaned in and kissed Joey on the mouth. For maybe half a second, Joey's fingers stayed on her cheek, her lips accepting, almost welcoming. Maybe only a quarter of a second. Then she jumped back in surprise, and Kaela felt herself hit the ground. She burst into tears and jumped up quickly, grabbing her shoes and her jacket.</p>
		<p>"Fuck, I'm so sorry, Joey, I'm so sorry..." her voice trailed off into a few broken sobs, and Joey, for a critical moment, couldn't remember how to think, and didn't move.</p>
		<p>"Kaela, wait a second!" But she was already out the bedroom door, going nowhere, anywhere. Without stopping to put on her own shoes or jacket, Joey ran after her. Kaela was out of the house in a flash, running blindly towards the road. She couldn't catch her breath, though, she was crying so hard, and Joey caught up with her, grabbing her arm. She yanked it away as if she'd been bitten, and then sunk to the ground in a daze of bitter tears. Joey swallowed her own terror and kneeled down next to her, hugging her tightly.</p>
		<p>"Don't be sorry, don't ever be sorry," Joey whispered fiercely as the buzzing energy that had charged them both all night began to leak away, leaving them weak, spent. They didn't speak for almost fifteen minutes, and they both felt so drained they might have stayed outside all night if it weren't biting cold. Joey got up first, the cold hitting her full-force as she pulled herself away from Kaela's body heat. "C'mon," she said softly, tugging Kaela to her feet. They walked slowly back to the house, as if in a daze, without looking at each other.</p>
